{
  "answer": "In Manusmṛti chapter 12 (work slug: unknown-manusmrti-347b76), 'guṇa' refers to the three constituent qualities (modes of nature) of the Self that pervade all beings and determine their character, actions, and rebirth. The three guṇas are:\n\n1. **Sattva** (purity/goodness) — equated with knowledge; perceived in the self as joined with pleasure, tranquil and pure-seeming; its characteristics include study of the Veda, tapas, purity, sense-control, Dharma, and contemplation of the Self. The characteristic of sattva is Dharma. Those who are predominantly sāttvic are reborn as gods. (Mn_12.24, 12.26, 12.27, 12.31, 12.37–38, 12.40)\n\n2. **Rajas** (passion) — equated with passion and aversion; perceived as joined with pain and unpleasing to the self, constantly captivating embodied beings; characteristics include taste for action, impatience, improper acts, and indulgence in sense-objects. The characteristic of rajas is worldly gain. Those who are predominantly rājasic are reborn as humans. (Mn_12.24, 12.26, 12.28, 12.32, 12.36–38, 12.40)\n\n3. **Tamas** (darkness/ignorance) — equated with ignorance; perceived as joined with delusion, unmanifest, of the nature of sense-objects, incapable of being reasoned about or known; characteristics include greed, sleep, lack of fortitude, cruelty, atheism, dissolute life, and carelessness. The characteristic of tamas is desire. Those who are predominantly tāmasic are reborn as beasts. (Mn_12.24, 12.26, 12.29, 12.33, 12.35–38, 12.40)\n\nThe chapter states that whichever guṇa predominates in a body at a given time makes that embodied being predominantly of that guṇa (Mn_12.25). The three guṇas also determine cycles of rebirth in ascending order of excellence: tamas → beasts, rajas → men, sattva → gods (Mn_12.40–41). Within each guṇa there are further subdivisions — low, middle, and high tāmasic/rājasic/sāttvic states — that correspond to increasingly elevated beings and rebirths.",
